{"slug": "enchanter", "root": "enchanter", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a caster of enchantments", "definition": "An enchanter works magic by the spoken or sung word — chanting spells that charm, bind, or transform. He differs from a conjurer, who summons spirits to do his will: the enchanter's power is in the incantation itself, the utterance that fascinates its hearer or reshapes the world. The feminine *enchantress* names the same art.", "history": "The word descends from Latin *incantare*, 'to sing a spell upon' (via Old French *enchanteur*) — literally a singer over things. The sung root stayed audible: the historian Claire Fanger even titled an essay 'Things Done Wisely by a Wise Enchanter' — about the very power that spoken words were once believed to hold, the same power this word has always named. The defining turn was literary rather than lexical. Geoffrey of Monmouth's twelfth-century Merlin became, as the *Routledge History of Medieval Magic* observes, the model for most later male enchanters, fixing the figure as a worker of transformative wonders. The word lands as both a folk charmer named in trial records and the romance sorcerer — a caster who sings.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Fanger, 'Things Done Wisely by a Wise Enchanter'", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)", "abstract": "A scholarly article on a strange medieval debate: could spoken words alone have real power? The author shows that some 13th-century thinkers, like Roger Bacon, argued certain words could work through natural (almost proto-scientific) causes, while others insisted that any word-magic that actually worked had to be secretly powered by demons."}, {"label": "Page & Rider, The Routledge History of Medieval Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)", "url": "https://www.routledge.com/The-Routledge-History-of-Medieval-Magic/Page-Rider/p/book/9781032093994", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A large reference collection that rounds up current scholarship on magic in medieval Europe (roughly 1100 to 1500), covering the texts people used, how the church and universities reacted, and how magic touched gender roles, art, medicine, and the early witch trials."}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. enchant (Latin incantare)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Latin", "origin": "Latin incantare 'to sing a spell on' (via Old French enchanteur)", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "The agent-noun of enchant; the -ess form (enchantress) feminised it. A singer of spells.", "hook": "The enchanter literally sings."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 9, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 9, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 11, "by_variant": {"enchanter": 7, "enchanters": 1, "enchantress": 1}, "first_year": 1995, "colors": {"U": 8, "W": 5, "G": 6, "R": 1, "B": 2}, "by_year": {"1995": 2, "1997": 1, "2008": 2, "2014": 2, "2016": 1, "2018": 2, "2023": 4, "2024": 4}}, "cards": [{"id": "ee0f883f-d7c9-4acf-a78f-f733b6f268d3", "name": "Zuran Enchanter", "set": "ICE", "set_name": "Ice Age", "released": "1995-06-03", "type_line": "Creature — Human Wizard", "rarity": "common", "colors": ["U"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/7/2/721edcef-f40a-4d43-9d80-26161dc425cb.jpg?1782721716", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/7/2/721edcef-f40a-4d43-9d80-26161dc425cb.jpg?1782721716", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/ice/111/zuran-enchanter?utm_source=api", "local": "img/enchanter/ee0f883f-d7c9-4acf-a78f-f733b6f268d3.jpg"}, {"id": "8b983a46-580f-4a94-8ef3-5253e503148e", "name": "Femeref Enchantress", "set": "VIS", "set_name": "Visions", "released": "1997-02-03", "type_line": "Creature — Human Druid", "rarity": "rare", "colors": ["G", "W"], 